<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-601-488  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 601 488.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  June 18 1990 v11 n25 p40(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Natural query language turns plain English into SQL; researchinstitute working toward putting language interface on chip.andO;(Battelle Memorial Institute)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Coursey, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Natural Language Query (NLQ), a Battelle Memorial Instituteproduct, is a program that turns a plain English request forinformation into a Structured Query Language (SQL) statement thatcan be read by several data bases.andP;  NLQ is easier to use thanother data base interfaces, however it is still necessary to usespecific phrasing and word choice.andP;  Battelle's interface runs on astandard microcomputer with 640Kbytes memory under MS-DOS.andP;  NLQconsists of three basic components: administration, communicationslibraries and an end-user component.andP;  The Institute is workingtoward integration of the language interface on a chip.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Structured Query LanguageData Base LanguagesQuery LanguagesFuture of ComputingBattelle Memorial InstituteNatural Language Interfaces.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>